subSubSection.paragraph:
Arthrobranchs of type C (cf. 
Ngoc-Ho 1981
), composed of deeply divided, narrow lamellae on either side of rachis.

Upogebiids represent deeply burrowing infauna, particularly abundant in coastal shallow waters ( Itani 2004 ;
Dworschak et al. 2012
), although many species have been described also from the sublittoral zone (e.g., Sakai 2006 , 2011 , 2015 ; Liu & Liu 2010 , 2013 ), of which the vast majority is rare. It is interesting to note that no species of Upogebiidae have been recorded from sublittoral depths in Sagami Bay, although investigations of the benthic fauna have been long continued from the late 19th century (
Takeda et al. 2006
; Fujita & Akasaka 2007 ;
Nakano et al. 2015
). The discovery of the present new species highlights the difficulty of inventory of the deeply burrowing infauna inhabiting the sublittoral or deeper zone in spite of its existence.
